{
  "text": "It is increasingly evident that adult age differences in memory need to be understood from a contextual perspective in which both intraindividual and interindividual variations in performance are considered within the context of multiple normative and nonnormative influences [CITATION_1] . One specific set of influences relates to culturally shared stereotypes about aging, which have been investigated in terms of self-stereotype effects on memory. This research has shown that older adults' memory performance can be affected through implicit and explicit situational cues that serve to activate aging stereotypes (for a review, see [CITATION_2] .",
  "correct_citation": {
